discussion_comments.comment_body:
@oranagra I removed the atomic refcount again because although it simplified the release of threads, it increased the overhead of obtaining refcount, and the performance dropped significantly (~5%) when there was no iothread. Therefore, I chose the earliest conservative solution, that is, to ensure the safe release of robj during flushdb async.
And I also tried to separate different robj, but this is extremely complex. I can't guarantee that it will be stably completed in 8.6(end of this week), so I have also put this solution on hold for now

@ShooterIT please also take a look.
